{{Accessory | Name=PlayStation 2 Multitap | Guid=3000-18 | Deck=The multitap increases the number of controller/memory card ports to four per multitap per original ports, of which there were two pair. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/24/10998-20078151273092667.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"10998-20078151273092667.jpg","path":"0\/24\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_medium,scale_super,square_mini,square_medium,square_small,screen_medium,square_avatar,scale_small,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":""},"background":[]}' />
==Overview== Produced for an era when party games demanded more than just two simultaneous players, the [[Platforms/PlayStation_2|PlayStation 2]] multitap plugs into one of the controller and memory card slots on the console, increasing the total number of controller ports from two to five. Plug a second multitap into the remaining ports on the console for an additional three players. Later versions of the device also provided extra memory card slots, allowing players to keep track of their individual statistics for games that would allow it.

{{Accessory | Name=PlayStation 2 Network Adaptor | Guid=3000-69 | Deck=A combined dial-up modem and Ethernet adapter released for the PlayStation 2, which plugs into the console's expansion bay and allows online play in certain games. It also enables installation of the PlayStation 2 Hard Disk Drive. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/5/59593/2604973-5182029015-418T3.jpg}}
<div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"2604973-5182029015-418T3.jpg","path":"5\/59593\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_small,square_mini,square_small,square_tiny,square_medium,scale_tiny,square_avatar,scale_medium,screen_medium,scale_large,scale_avatar,scale_super,screen_kubrick","caption":""},"background":[]}' />
==Overview== The Network Adaptor for [[Platforms/PlayStation_2|PlayStation 2]] was released in July 2001 in Japan, August 2002 in North America, and June 2003 in Europe. It functions as both an Ethernet network adapter for broadband Internet, and a modem for dial-up. In North America, the adapter launched with several [[Concepts/Online|online-capable]] games: [[Games/SOCOM_U_S_Navy_SEALs|SOCOM: U.S. Navy SEALs]], [[Games/NFL_GameDay_2003|NFL GameDay 2003]], [[Games/Madden_NFL_2003|Madden NFL 2003]], [[Games/NFL_2K3|NFL 2K3]], and [[Games/Twisted_Metal_Black_ONLINE|Twisted Metal: Black ONLINE]], which could be obtained for free using a mail-order coupon that came with the adapter. The slimline PS2 does not support the adapter, though later revisions of the system include a built-in Ethernet port. No slimline PS2s support the HDD, however, which prevents users from playing online games like [[Games/Final_Fantasy_XI_Online|Final Fantasy XI]] that require a hard drive.

{{Accessory | Name=Super Game Boy | Guid=3000-123 | Deck=The Super Game Boy is an accessory for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System that allows players to play Game Boy games on a television. | Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/1992/3395511-1262717384-91iGv.jpg}}
